> So you are telling me that behavior displayed in video below is okay?...

Yes that is okay.

However there is still room for optimise your code.

Change this:
```dart
Column(
  children: [
    Container(
      height: MediaQuery.of(context).size.height / 2,
      width: MediaQuery.of(context).size.width / 2,
      color: Colors.red,
    ),
    Expanded(
      child: ListView(
        children: List.generate(100000, (index) => Text('index: $index')),
      ),
    )
  ],
);
```

To:
```dart
return Column(
  children: [
    const RedContainer(),
    Expanded(
      child: ListView.builder(
        itemBuilder: (context, index) => Text('index: $index'),
      ),
    )
  ],
);

class RedContainer extends StatelessWidget {
  const RedContainer({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Container(
      height: MediaQuery.of(context).size.height / 2,
      width: MediaQuery.of(context).size.width / 2,
      color: Colors.red,
    );
  }
}
```

> Was it always like this in flutter or it was caused by one of the PRs ([this one](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/114459) or [that one](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/118004), specifically)?

#114459 is one of my favorite changes, for instance your first screen won't rebuild if user changes text scalfactor if you write `MediaQuery.sizeOf(context)` instead of `MediaQuery.of(context).size` so your `build` method will rerun only if size changed but not other properties on `MediaQueryData`

#118004 it just splits `MediaQuery`

Check out this code, this is not using `MediaQuery` but `Theme` and you can observe the first screen also calls build:
```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  runApp(const MainApp());
}

// do not use global variables like this, this is for demonstration purposes
final globalTheme = ValueNotifier<ThemeData>(ThemeData.light());

class MainApp extends StatelessWidget {
  const MainApp({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return AnimatedBuilder(
      animation: globalTheme,
      builder: (context, child) => MaterialApp(
        theme: globalTheme.value,
        home: const FirstScreen(),
      ),
    );
  }
}

class FirstScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  const FirstScreen({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    print('build');

    // dependency on Theme
    final theme = Theme.of(context);

    return Scaffold(
      body: Center(
        child: ElevatedButton(
          onPressed: () {
            Navigator.of(context).push<void>(
              MaterialPageRoute<void>(
                builder: (context) => const SecondScreen(),
              ),
            );
          },
          child: const Text('Go to SecondScreen'),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}

class SecondScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  const SecondScreen({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Scaffold(
      body: Center(
        child: ElevatedButton(
          onPressed: () {
            globalTheme.value = globalTheme.value.brightness == Brightness.light ? ThemeData.dark() : ThemeData.light();
          },
          child: const Text('Change Theme'),
        ),
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

Do not forget widgets are blueprints and Flutter framework (`RenderObjectWidget`) is smart enough to avoid rerenders if nothing changed in the Widget / blueprint.

> https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/54116985/242359873-363e3bfc-39a9-4e7d-af57-eac289182877.mov

On this video I can see the **UI Thread** ( _where Dart code runs_ ) causes the jank and **not the Raster Thread** ( _GPU Thread_ ) that is why you should use `ListView.builder`.

I don't like the fact that once a `BuildContext` becomes dependent on an `InheritedWidget`, it stays so until the end of its lifecycle.

For instance, when `ElevatedButton`'s `onTap` creates a dependency on `_InheritedTheme`. Consequently, build method called again when `ThemeData` is changed, which doesn't make dependency on `_InheritedTheme` any more inside `build` method, it is still considered dependent on `_InheritedTheme` because `onTap` made it so.

Example code:

```dart
class MyWidget extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyWidget({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return ElevatedButton(
      onPressed: () {
        print(Theme.of(context).primaryColor);
      },
      child: const Text('Press me and BuildContext will be forever dependent on _InheritedTheme even if build method does not use Theme.of().'),
    );
  }
}
```

This way you cannot use tricks like this:

```dart
class MyWidget extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyWidget({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    if (!ModalRoute.of<dynamic>(context)!.isCurrent) {
      // when route is not current just return empty Widget
      // Theme.of(context) is not called this time however BuildContext is already dependent on Theme
      return const SizedBox.shrink();
    }

    final theme = Theme.of(context);
    return Text('Dependency on Theme', style: TextStyle(color: theme.primaryColor));
  }
}
```

